  <bioghist id="c78ac1ec984e33bd682011bebb4cd6b3">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Christine Wing is a strategist, scholar, activist, and educator within the fields of philanthropy and international peace and security. From 1995 to 2004, she worked as a Program Officer at the Ford Foundation.</p><p>Wing joined the Ford Foundation in 1995 as a Program Officer in the International Affairs Program. Following the Foundation's program reorganization in 1996, Wing was moved into the Peace and Social Justice Program (PSJ) Human Rights and International Cooperation unit (HRIC). While a Program Officer in the HRIC, she focused on the following initiatives: disarmament and the control of weapons, reduction in the amount of society's resources dedicated to military purposes, and support for local and regional capacity to address peace and conflict issues (Reflection and Close-Out Memo: Program on International Peace and Security, Human Rights and International Cooperation Unit, November 29, 2002, Ford Foundation records, Catalogued Reports, Reports 13949-17726 (FA739F), Report 017092). Wing moved to the Governance and Civil Society unit of PSJ in 2002.</p><p>Prior to joining the Ford Foundation, Wing worked at the American Friends Service Committee (AFSC) from 1979 to 1989, first as the organization's National Representative for Economic Rights and then as Coordinator for the National Disarmament Program.</p><p>Wing started consulting for foundations, nonprofits, and international organizations in 2006 and started Chris Wing Consulting in 2016. She also worked as an adjunct professor and researcher at New York University between 2005 and 2015. </p><p>Wing is a member of the Board of Directors for the Arms Control Association. She completed her undergraduate education at Wellesley College, earned a Master's Degree in city and regional planning from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, and earned a Ph.D. in international security studies from the Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs at Princeton University.</p>  </bioghist>
